
===================================
📌 1. Finglish Version (Persian Latin Script)
===================================

📖 **Tashrih:**
    Dastoor `debuild` baraye sakhtane package Debian az source code estefade mishavad. In dastoor barname-haye lazem baraye compilation va build kardan ra faraham mikonad va package .deb ra tolid mikonad.

⚙️ **Gozine-ha:**
    🔹 `debuild -us`  --> 🔑 Package ra bedune sign kardan source files misazad.
    🔹 `debuild -uc`  --> 📦 Package ra bedune sign kardan .changes file misazad.
    🔹 `debuild -b`   --> 🏗 Faghat binary package-ha ra misazad (source package nemisazad).
    🔹 `debuild -S`   --> 🧩 Faghat source package ra misazad (binary package nemisazad).

🛠 **Mesal-ha:**

    $ debuild

    🔹 Sakhte package Debian ba estefade az setting-haye default.

    $ debuild -us -uc

    🔹 Sakhte package Debian bedune sign kardan source files va .changes file.

✅ **Mesal sade:**

    $ debuild -b

    🔹 Faghat binary package-ha sakhte mishavand, agar shirkat dar sakhtane source package nadashte bashid.

===================================
📌 2. English Version
===================================

📖 **Description:**
    The `debuild` command is used to build a Debian package from source code. This command sets up the necessary environment for compilation and building, and it produces a .deb package.

⚙️ **Options:**
    🔹 `debuild -us`  --> 🔑 Build the package without signing the source files.
    🔹 `debuild -uc`  --> 📦 Build the package without signing the .changes file.
    🔹 `debuild -b`   --> 🏗 Build only the binary packages (does not build the source package).
    🔹 `debuild -S`   --> 🧩 Build only the source package (does not build the binary packages).

🛠 **Examples:**

    $ debuild

    🔹 Build the Debian package using default settings.

    $ debuild -us -uc

    🔹 Build the Debian package without signing the source files and .changes file.

✅ **Simple Example:**

    $ debuild -b

    🔹 Only the binary packages are built, useful if you are not involved in building the source package.
